title: For Sale:  High resolution firearm photography.. For art or sale!
postcontent:
Why use a low resolution cell phone picture or other low end camera to represent an item you'd like to sell. Lots of research shows that a better picture has higher chances of selling an item.

For a very reasonable fee, I can use my high end professional camera to photograph your item as you'd like it done. Image editing included to really make the picture stand out.

If you're selling an old VCR, a cell phone picture or $100 sony camera might work. When you intend to represent a near thousand dollar (or more) item in an attractive and detailed manner, my opinion is that the picture SHOULD do it justice.

I am not a professional photographer... I bought a nice camera for a hobby and I also enjoy firearms... This is a fun and interesting blend of the two, at a much lower cost than a professional studio.


I charge $20 for up to 30 mins and $25 for a 30-45 min session, with editing included afterwards until you are satisfied.

NOTE: For safety reasons, I require a copy of your valid FOID and matching Illinois ID before we meet, and I will provide the same.

If you want to display a particular firearm as an artistic piece in your home, I can do that as well. Instead of taking "product" shots, I can take artistic or interesting shots of the firearm that will be sure to get noticed. I have several resources for printing that you can choose from (at an additional cost.. I don't print them)

Whether you intend to use it on armslist or elsewhere, high quality photographs are a must for any serious seller.

I purchased this pistol brand new some time ago. I sent it to Robar for the custom finish shortly thereafter (a little over $300) and have maintained and babied it ever since. This pistol has never seen the inside of a holster. The throat of the chamber is polished and the bore is exceptionally clean. I attempted to demonstrate this in the photos but it's hard to see. There are some very faint marks from the squeeze cocker which you can see in one of the pictures at the Imageshack link below. I took a close up of it.

Comes with two magazines, original serial-numbered box/case, documentation, originally-supplied cleaning tools, and a cool vintage HK/Benelli patch that I got elsewhere.

This weapon has never misfired even when limp-wristed (it's an HK, come on.) It is honestly the most accurate non-scoped handgun I've ever shot. I'm a piss-poor shot with a handgun and this P7 made me look good every time I fired it at a target. I hate to part with it because I love it but I'm getting out of gun-collecting. I only need one and I couldn't bear to stick a pistol this nice in a holster inside my waistband.

I prefer local pickup in the Portage Wisconsin area. You can examine it and be pleased without a hassle. (I will *consider* shipping to your FFL in another state but be advised: I will not play games. I require the postage and insurance to my PayPal as well as the cost of the pistol and you will immediately get exactly what you see. There will be no returns and BS after somebody else beyond my sight handles it for obvious reasons.) 

It actually looks *better* than the iPhone photos. You will get what you see and it will be fully-functional. You may examine even more photos at higher resolution and detail here:  http://imageshack.us/g/1/10286780/

Thanks for looking and I hope you find what you're looking for regardless of whether you buy this firearm or another. Have a great day.

title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 94
location: Kent  Auburn  Puyallup, Southwest Washington, Washington
postcontent: Safe Queen. Winchester Model 94, 30-30 Win., New, Nice Wood. I did the research and this gun was made in 1980. This is the last of the real Winchesters. Winchester was bought out in late 1981 or early 1982 by USRA. USRA discontinued there Model 94AE in 2006. The collectable Winchesters are pre-64 models because they were made from billet steel and machined parts. Winchester for whatever reason in 1964 went with a less expensive process whereby they used cast and stamped parts. (pot metal) In 1979 Winchester got there crap together and went back to making guns the right way. From 1979 thru 1981 they were made from billet steel like the pre-64 guns. (NICE) That's when things went astray for Winchester and they were bought out by USRA. So there you have it. This is the last of the Original Winchester Model 94's Made the right way in USA, by Winchester. Still new @ 33yrs. old. No cheep junk here.  NOTE: If your seeking an old rusted up piece of crap to toss in your truck, this is not the gun for you. IF your seeking a beautiful Safe Queen with beautiful wood to compliment your other pieces in your collection, this is the right one for you.  **Open to Trades**

 The gun is all Palmetto State Armory and was purchased as a complete rifle with the following upgrades:

 Chrome Bolt Carrier, Troy Defense Battle Quad Rail (very nice and lightweight), Magpul flip up rear sight, C Products 30 round magazine and a Bulldog Case.

 It has a 1/7 twist 16" chrome lined barrel with flash hider and it is chambered in 5.56x45mm, it is a carbine with a mid length quad rail on it with plenty of room for anything you would want to mount on it, plus a complete set of snap on rail covers in case you want to hold the rifle by the quad rail. It Has a 6 position adjustable stock.

 ALSO INCLUDED BUT IS A MAGPUL FOREGRIP WITH A LASER SIGHT MOUNTED TO THE SIDE OF THE RAIL, THE BUTTON FOR THE LASER IS ON THE FOREGRIP AND IT MAKES FOR A NICE TACTICAL TOOL OR EASY ACQUISITION ON A TARGET.

 The shine you see is a coat of oil I wiped it down with after I cleaned it the last time I shot it, I always put a light coat on my guns before I put them in the safe, the camera flash makes it look a lot shinier than it really is.

 This is a great rifle and I am going to regret selling it one day. I am not looking for any trades but if you have to have the rifle and are offering something nice and attractive I will at least hear your pitch.
